<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Colorado Springs-2/24/02-Clean Bathrooms<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.84)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6993'>Patrick "Pappy" Napier</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6993&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 5, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> 	It was time once again to play in one of the almost weekly tournaments we have here in southern Colorado.  This one was being held at Gamer&#8217;s Haven, a new gaming store that apparently has quite a group of LOTR players that hang out there for open gaming and now for League play.  The event was being hosted by Ian Monteith and it was his first attempt at running a Decipher tournament.  Ian has been playing Star Wars since day one, and is currently 4th in the world for LOTR.  I was playing good old Rangers and Nazgul for this event, and since none of my normal playtest group could get the day off from work or wives, I went alone.  Fellow Rider of Rohan Brian Montez was there, along with some of the regular Hobby town crowd, Danny Hummel and Joe Schlagheck the key players among them.  We waited and waited for Ian to show up, and the boy was late to his own tournament because he was helping his Dad finish a level on some Playstation game.  What ? If somebody wants to get this tournament report started, give me a Hell yeah !  What ? <br>
<br>
GAME ONE <br>
<br>
vs.  Joe Schlagheck  Hobbit Rangers / Uruk-Hai<br>
<br>
Joe has certainly improved his game over the last few weeks, so I was thinking my first game would be a challenge.  Joe bid madly to go first, so my Nazgul were set up for Sites 2 and 3.  At Site 2, Pippen was trampled under the hooves of a Black Rider, then his Aragorn bit the dust at Site 4.  His Uruk were barely getting through the Archery my Rangers were throwing at them, so I was in good shape.  Legolas died shortly after at Site 6, and Boromir finally took a dirt nap at Site 8.  Ulaire Toldea turned his blank stare to Frodo, who lost control of his bladder into his Little Hobbit Breeches ( Look for this Possession in Realm of the Elf Lords ! ) and fell down dead. <br>
<br>
FW +3 / +3<br>
<br>
I was relieved that my deck came out better for me than Joe&#8217;s did, and I was off to a decent start at the Haven.  Now it was time to play some people I was not very familiar with.<br>
<br>
GAME TWO <br>
<br>
vs.  Jason Sengermano ( or something close to that anyway )  Rangers and Ringwraiths<br>
<br>
Jason bids to go first and flips the Pony for Site 1 and Arwen / Legolas to start.  Hmmm, this should be fun.  We basically went back and forth stalling each other and moving one site at a time.  His Arwen perished at site 3 to an early Black Breath / Blade Tip combo, and his Sam was slaughtered at the dreaded Bridge.  On the last turn, Jason moves to site 9 with Aragorn, Boromir and Legolas left.  I played two Big Fierce Black Rider Guys, knowing that they would kill some Fellowship fools and get to Frodo.  But Jason had other plans, brilliant plans.  He played Valiant man of the West and let Aragorn get overwhelmed to the first wave of attacks, leaving Boromir and Legolas to take on the second wave.  When the dust settled, Jason&#8217;s Frodo stood all alone at the end of the Adventure Path, with clean Little Hobbit Breeches ( known as &#8220; britches &#8220; in the southern United States and Texas ) to boot.  <br>
<br>
FL +1 / +4<br>
<br>
Well, that should put me out of the running for first, unless Danny Hummel takes a loss some time during the day.  At this point I really need a bathroom.  I walked into Gamer&#8217;s Haven&#8217;s restroom and was swept away to another place, a cleaner place that smelled of potpourri and Lysol.  Angels sang as I realized this was absolutely one of the cleanest public restroom&#8217;s I have ever seen, and it was in a gaming store !  Amazing. <br>
<br>
GAME THREE <br>
<br>
vs. Krystal Warrell Hobbits / Morning Moods ( Uruk-Hai )<br>
<br>
Krystal is a young girl, about 15 I think.  She has played at one of my local tournaments and fared pretty well, coming in somewhere in the middle of the pack.  She has a pile of about 4,876 tokens, so we decide to use hers for this game, because we wouldn&#8217;t want to clutter up the table.  Anyway, she goes first, pulling Aragorn with the Pony ( imagine that ) and moves on to Wetherhills to face some Nasty Nazgul.  I didn&#8217;t really keep track of this game because it was over too fast.  Basically I killed Aragorn, Merry, Pippin, and Sam all before Site 6.  At Site 6, Frodo crapped his Little Hobbit Breeches at the site of Ulaire Whatever.  He was so embarrassed he keeld over and died.  Krystal made some feeble attempts with her Uruks to cause some damage, but they could not get through the Archery.  When I did let them get through it was when I had Skirmish events to handle them with.  Krystal calls her Shadow deck Morning Moods, because I guess each Uruk-Hai card reminds her of one of her friends when they first get up in the morning.  Ahh, to be a 15 year old girl again.  <br>
<br>
FW +3 / +7 <br>
<br>
Well, I hate getting such easy victories, but that&#8217;s what happens when you mess up and lose.  Now I should be paired up in the winners again, right ?  Wrong<br>
<br>
GAME FOUR <br>
<br>
vs. Patrick ( You betternot call him Pat ) Little   Gandalf and Friends<br>
<br>
Im serious, this guy would not let you call him Pat.  I did, and I thought I was going to be murdered.  So if you see this guy at a local event, say &#8220; Hi, PATRICK, how are you this fine day ? &#8220; otherwise you&#8217;re in for serious trouble.  Anyway, he bids to start some Site 1, it doesn&#8217;t matter really, because Sites 2 and 3 is were PATRICK gets whooped up on.  When he gets to the Site 4 , Aragorn and Legolas both die to a heavily pumped up Ulaire Attea. Something happened here when PATRICK forgot to heal at the Sanctuary, but we played it out and it didn&#8217;t matter in the overall scheme of things, because he was overwhelmed anyway.  The only difference was directed Archery, which I would have avoided with All Bladfes Perish anyway.  PATRICK was very cool about the whole thing.  At Site 5, the Witch King with a Nazgul Sword layeth the Smackdown on Gandalf&#8217;s candy a$s, and he could definitely smell what the Lord of Angmar was cookin&#8217;.  At Site 6 Ulaire Toldea came out to play with Frodo, but at the first whiff of Frodo&#8217;s messed in Little Hobbit Breeches, he got so mad he killed him. <br>
<br>
FW +3 / +10 <br>
<br>
Well, okay, NOW I should be paired up with someone on the winning side of things.  As it turns out, I get paired against Danny Hummel, both of us having three wins and one loss.  If I win this one, I should win the tournament.  Danny had other ideas.<br>
<br>
GAME FIVE<br>
<br>
vs. Danny Hummel Hobbits / Moria Swarm<br>
<br>
Danny and I talked a little before the game, and we both knew what the other was playing.  He bid to go first to deny me the Pony, which was fine, because that gave me Sites 2 and 3.  Somehow he sneaks through these dangerous Sites with nary a scratch.  When my Fellowship gets to Site 4, all Hell breaks loose.  The Cave Troll killed Aragorn, the anchor of my deck.  At Site 5, the Cave Troll came out again, with some friends, to finish off Legolas.  Arwen and Frodo can&#8217;t survive the Swarms, and Frodo gets seriously overwhelmed, pooping in his Little Hobbit Breeches all the way through Moria.<br>
<br>
FL +1 / + 11 <br>
<br>
So, with opponent points all totaled, I end up in 4th place, again.  Brian Montez took third, and Joe Schlagheck pulled off second place.  Danny Hummel wins the whole deal.  Ian handed out prize support, and I pulled a rare Boromir, which I promptly traded for a load of foils.  I also won the Random Guy Who Came To A Tournament And Didn&#8217;t Win Prize, so I will be getting a common foil in the mail sometime by the year 2026, when I can show it to Buck Rodgers and reminisce about the days of &#8220; cars &#8220; powered by fossil fuels and NASA&#8217;s &#8220; Space Program &#8220; <br>
<br>
<br>
PROPS<br>
<br>
To Ian Monteith, for running a smooth event and making good rulings.  Great job, rookie. J<br>
<br>
To Danny Hummel, for playing Hobbits and winning ( it was all about the Shadow ) <br>
<br>
To Gamer&#8217;s Haven, for having the cleanest bathroom of any Gaming / Hobby / Comic book store I have ever had the privilege of urinating in.  ( It was even cleaner than Collectormania&#8217;s ! ) <br>
<br>
To PATRICK Little, for not taking any lip and refusing to let people call him Pat.  <br>
<br>
To Jason S., for the brilliant end game move.  It would have been another story if hadn&#8217;t pulled that off.<br>
<br>
SLOPS<br>
<br>
To me, for taking fourth.<br>
<br>
To all the other Gaming stores who don&#8217;t keep their bathrooms as clean as Gamer&#8217;s Haven.<br>
<br>
<br>
